Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 07:58:53 -0500
From: Robin B. Lake <rbl@hal.EPBI.CWRU.Edu>

As a sushi fan and a friend and neighbor of a sushi bar owner:
Here in Cleveland, there are two sources for sushi-quality fish. (1) A
seafood supply wholesaler who has a trained sushi fish inspector and
also buys sealed packages from a distributor who inspects each fish,
and (2) a nationwide chain of in-grocery sushi stands. Re: (2) Their fish
arrives via air freight each morning from a central facility in
California (Being located just below my office, I see the delivery
each morning).
>From Steven Jay Gould's book about "Jewish Grandmothers", one can gain
an appreciation of the risks of uninspected undercooked fish.
The national sushi shop chain is "AFC" and they have a Web site.
--
Robin Lake
Environmental Modeling Inc.
e-mail: rbl@po.cwru.edu

[3
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 15:40:58 -0500
From: Schantz, Peter M. <pms1@cdc.gov>

A useful publication is available entitled "Fish parasites and human
health" by JA Sakanari, M. Moser and TL Deardorff, Report No.
T-CSGCP-034 Sea Grant College, UC, La Jolla, CA. Copies can be
obtained for $4 from Calif. Sea Grant College, UC, 9500 Gilman Dr., ,
Dept. 0232, La Jolla, CA 92093-0232. It covers life cycles, factors
affecting transmission., prevention, politics and public education.
As far as the dangers of sushi are concerned it is my understanding that
the problems are minimal when the sushi is served at a restaurant by a
qualified sushi chef. The great majority of cases of parasitism derived
from sushi, both in Japan where it is relatively common, and in the
U.S., where it is rare, are derived from home prepared sushi. Sushi
chefs in Japan undergo an extended and rigorous training program which
includes instruction on how to search for and avoid parasitized seafood.
--
Peter M. Schantz, VMD, PhD
