[4
Date: Tue, 17 Mar 1998 11:55:16 -1000
From: Richard Frankel <rfrankel@hawaii.edu>

Because of concerns about sushi, which were not directed particularly at
sushi bars (where sushi is prepared to order) but more at vendors who sell
sushi made earlier in the day, Hawaii enacted the following regulations. I
believe these went into effect early in 1997, but am not certain of the
date.
For all potentially hazardous foods, the requirement is that they be
maintained at or below forty-five degrees Fahrenheit or at or above one
hundred forty degrees Fahrenheit during display and service. (Sorry to use
Fahrenheit, but this is the U.S.!)
The following exception was created to enable vendors to continue to sell
sushi.
Potentially hazardous food may be kept at a temperature between forty-five
degrees Fahrenheit and one hundred forty degrees Fahrenheit if the following
requirements are met:
1) The total time that the food is within this temperature range does not
exceed four hours.
2) Foods are labelled as to the time the food is removed from safe
temperature control, or labelled as to the time by which the food must be
served or discarded.
3) Foods not properly labelled as to time, or beyond the four hour limit,
must be discarded.
--
